    <h2 id="79">79. Ethics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Ethics is the philosophical study of moral principles that govern behavior and decision-making.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Theories</strong><br>
        - <strong>Utilitarianism:</strong> Advocates for actions that maximize overall happiness or utility.<br>
        - <strong>Deontology:</strong> Focuses on adherence to moral duties and rules, regardless of outcomes.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Ethics guides personal conduct, professional practices, and policy-making, addressing issues such as justice, rights, and responsibility.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Mill, J. S. (1863). <em>Utilitarianism</em>. Parker, Son, and Bourn.<br>
        - Kant, I. (1785). <em>Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals</em>. Cambridge University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="80">80. Evolutionary Biology</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Evolutionary biology studies the origins, development, and diversification of life on Earth through the process of evolution.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Concepts</strong><br>
        - <strong>Natural Selection:</strong> The process by which advantageous traits become more common in a population.<br>
        - <strong>Genetic Drift:</strong> Random changes in allele frequencies in a population.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Evolutionary biology helps explain the diversity of life, evolutionary relationships, and the adaptation of organisms to their environments.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Darwin, C. (1859). <em>On the Origin of Species</em>. John Murray.<br>
        - Futuyma, D. J. (2017). <em>Evolutionary Biology</em>. Sinauer Associates.
    </p>

    <h2 id="81">81. Finance</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Finance is the management of money, investments, and other financial instruments.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Corporate Finance:</strong> Focuses on financial management and strategies within companies.<br>
        - <strong>Investment:</strong> Involves the analysis and selection of investment opportunities.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Finance is essential for personal financial planning, corporate financial management, and investment strategies.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Brealey, R. A., Myers, S. C., & Allen, F. (2017). <em>Principles of Corporate Finance</em>. McGraw-Hill.<br>
        - Merton, R. C., & Bodie, Z. (1995). <em>A Conceptual Framework for Analyzing the Financial Environment</em>. In <em>The Theory and Practice of Investment Management</em>.
    </p>

    <h2 id="82">82. Game Theory</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Game theory is the study of mathematical models of strategic interaction among rational decision-makers.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Concepts</strong><br>
        - <strong>Nash Equilibrium:</strong> A situation in which no player can benefit by changing their strategy while others keep theirs unchanged.<br>
        - <strong>Zero-Sum Games:</strong> Scenarios where one player's gain is equivalent to another player's loss.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Game theory is applied in economics, political science, and evolutionary biology to analyze competitive and cooperative interactions.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Nash, J. F. (1950). <em>Equilibrium Points in N-Person Games</em>. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.<br>
        - Osbourne, M. J., & Rubinstein, A. (1994). <em>A Course in Game Theory</em>. MIT Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="83">83. Geopolitics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Geopolitics examines the influence of geographic factors on international politics and power relations.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Strategic Geography:</strong> Analysis of how geographic locations impact strategic interests and conflicts.<br>
        - <strong>Resource Distribution:</strong> Study of how access to resources affects global power dynamics.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Geopolitics informs foreign policy, international relations, and strategic planning by considering geographic and resource-related factors.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Mearsheimer, J. J. (2001). <em>The Tragedy of Great Power Politics</em>. Free Press.<br>
        - Kaplan, R. D. (2009). <em>The Revenge of Geography: What the Map Tells Us About Coming Conflicts and the Battle Against Fate</em>. Random House.
    </p>

    <h2 id="84">84. Geology</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Geology is the scientific study of the Earth, including its materials, structures, and processes.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Mineralogy:</strong> Study of minerals and their properties.<br>
        - <strong>Paleontology:</strong> Examination of fossils to understand past life forms and environments.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Geology is crucial for natural resource exploration, understanding natural hazards, and studying Earth's history.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Marshak, S. (2012). <em>Earth: Portrait of a Planet</em>. W.W. Norton & Company.<br>
        - Press, F., & Siever, R. (2001). <em>Understanding Earth</em>. W.H. Freeman and Company.
    </p>

    <h2 id="85">85. Health Economics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Health economics studies the efficiency and effectiveness of healthcare systems and the allocation of resources in health care.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Cost-Effectiveness Analysis:</strong> Evaluation of the relative costs and outcomes of different healthcare interventions.<br>
        - <strong>Health Policy:</strong> Analysis of policies aimed at improving healthcare access, quality, and outcomes.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Health economics informs healthcare decision-making, policy development, and resource allocation to improve health outcomes.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Drummond, M. F., Sculpher, M. J., Claxton, K., et al. (2015). <em>Methods for the Economic Evaluation of Health Care Programmes</em>. Oxford University Press.<br>
        - Culyer, A. J., & Newhouse, J. P. (2000). <em>Handbook of Health Economics</em>. Elsevier.
    </p>

    <h2 id="86">86. History of Science</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>The history of science explores the development of scientific knowledge and practices over time.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Scientific Revolutions:</strong> Examination of major shifts in scientific understanding, such as the Copernican and Newtonian revolutions.<br>
        - <strong>Scientific Method:</strong> Study of the evolution of methods and approaches used in scientific inquiry.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Understanding the history of science provides insights into how scientific knowledge evolves and influences contemporary science and technology.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Kuhn, T. S. (1962). <em>The Structure of Scientific Revolutions</em>. University of Chicago Press.<br>
        - Jacob, C. (2006). <em>The Scientific Revolution: A Brief History with Documents</em>. Bedford/St. Martin's.
    </p>

    <h2 id="87">87. Human Resources Management</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Human resources management (HRM) focuses on recruiting, managing, and developing an organization's workforce.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Talent Acquisition:</strong> Strategies for recruiting and hiring skilled employees.<br>
        - <strong>Employee Development:</strong> Programs and initiatives for training and career development.
    </p>
   
    <h2 id="92">92. Mathematical Logic</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Mathematical logic studies formal systems and their applications in mathematics and computer science.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Proof Theory:</strong> Examination of formal proofs and their structures.<br>
        - <strong>Model Theory:</strong> Study of the relationships between formal systems and their interpretations.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Mathematical logic underpins the development of algorithms, programming languages, and formal verification methods.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Ebbinghaus, H.-D., Flum, J., & Thomas, W. (1994). <em>Mathematical Logic</em>. Springer.<br>
        - Enderton, H. B. (2001). <em>A Mathematical Introduction to Logic</em>. Academic Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="93">93. Mathematical Statistics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Mathematical statistics involves the application of mathematical methods to the collection, analysis, and interpretation of data.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Probability Theory:</strong> The study of random events and their likelihood.<br>
        - <strong>Statistical Inference:</strong> Techniques for drawing conclusions about populations based on sample data.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Mathematical statistics is used in various fields, including scientific research, economics, and engineering, to make data-driven decisions and predictions.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Casella, G., & Berger, R. L. (2002). <em>Statistical Inference</em>. Duxbury Press.<br>
        - Lehmann, E. L., & Casella, G. (2006). <em>Theory of Point Estimation</em>. Springer.
    </p>

    <h2 id="94">94. Metaphysics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Metaphysics is the branch of philosophy concerned with the nature of reality and existence.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Topics</strong><br>
        - <strong>Ontology:</strong> Study of the nature of being and existence.<br>
        - <strong>Identity and Change:</strong> Examination of how objects persist through time and change.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Metaphysics explores fundamental questions about reality, identity, and the nature of objects and their properties.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Aristotle. (350 B.C.E.). <em>Metaphysics</em>. (Translated by W. D. Ross).<br>
        - Kripke, S. A. (1980). <em>Naming and Necessity</em>. Harvard University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="95">95. Neuroscience</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Neuroscience is the study of the nervous system and its impact on behavior and cognitive functions.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Neuroanatomy:</strong> Study of the structure of the nervous system.<br>
        - <strong>Neurophysiology:</strong> Examination of the functions and processes of the nervous system.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Neuroscience informs our understanding of brain function, neurological disorders, and cognitive processes.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Bear, M. F., Connors, B. W., & Paradiso, M. A. (2015). <em>Neuroscience: Exploring the Brain</em>. Lippincott Williams & Wilkins.<br>
        - Kandel, E. R., Schwartz, J. H., & Jessell, T. M. (2012). <em>Principles of Neural Science</em>. McGraw-Hill.
    </p>

    <h2 id="96">96. Organizational Behavior</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Organizational behavior studies how individuals and groups act within organizations and how organizations respond to their environment.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Motivation:</strong> Examination of factors that drive employee performance and satisfaction.<br>
        - <strong>Leadership:</strong> Study of leadership styles and their impact on organizational effectiveness.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Organizational behavior helps improve management practices, enhance employee engagement, and foster a positive organizational culture.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Robbins, S. P., & Judge, T. A. (2019). <em>Organizational Behavior</em>. Pearson.<br>
        - Hackman, J. R., & Oldham, G. R. (1976). <em>Motivation through Design of Work: Test of a Theory</em>. Organizational Behavior and Human Performance.
    </p>

    <h2 id="97">97. Philosophy</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Philosophy is the study of fundamental questions regarding existence, knowledge, ethics, and reasoning.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Epistemology:</strong> The study of knowledge and belief.<br>
        - <strong>Ethics:</strong> Examination of moral principles and values.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Philosophy provides critical thinking skills, ethical frameworks, and theoretical insights applicable in various fields including law, science, and personal decision-making.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Plato. (c. 380 B.C.E.). <em>The Republic</em>. (Translated by Allan Bloom).<br>
        - Russell, B. (1912). <em>The Problems of Philosophy</em>. Oxford University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="98">98. Physical Chemistry</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Physical chemistry explores the physical principles underlying chemical systems and processes.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Thermodynamics:</strong> Study of energy changes and their effects on chemical reactions.<br>
        - <strong>Quantum Chemistry:</strong> Examination of how quantum mechanics explains chemical phenomena.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Physical chemistry aids in understanding reaction mechanisms, material properties, and the design of new chemical processes.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Atkins, P., & de Paula, J. (2014). <em>Physical Chemistry</em>. W.H. Freeman and Company.<br>
        - Levine, I. N. (2009). <em>Physical Chemistry: Principles and Applications in Biological Sciences</em>. Pearson.
    </p>

    <h2 id="99">99. Political Science</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Political science is the study of political systems, behavior, and governance.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Comparative Politics:</strong> Analysis of different political systems and their functions.<br>
        - <strong>International Relations:</strong> Study of interactions between states and international organizations.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Political science informs public policy, electoral strategies, and the understanding of political dynamics and institutions.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Dahl, R. A. (1989). <em>Democracy and Its Critics</em>. Yale University Press.<br>
        - Held, D. (2006). <em>Models of Democracy</em>. Stanford University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="100">100. Psychology</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Psychology is the scientific study of behavior and mental processes.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Cognitive Psychology:</strong> Examination of mental processes such as perception, memory, and problem-solving.<br>
        - <strong>Clinical Psychology:</strong> Study of mental health disorders and therapeutic techniques.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Psychology contributes to mental health treatment, understanding human behavior, and improving educational and organizational practices.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Myers, D. G. (2014). <em>Psychology</em>. Worth Publishers.<br>
        - Durand, V. M., & Barlow, D. H. (2014). <em>Essentials of Abnormal Psychology</em>. Cengage Learning.
    </p>

    <h2 id="101">101. Quantum Mechanics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Quantum mechanics is a fundamental theory in physics that describes the behavior of particles at the atomic and subatomic levels.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Concepts</strong><br>
        - <strong>Wave-Particle Duality:</strong> The concept that particles like electrons exhibit both wave-like and particle-like properties.<br>
        - <strong>Uncertainty Principle:</strong> Werner Heisenberg's principle that asserts it's impossible to precisely measure both the position and momentum of a particle simultaneously.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Quantum mechanics is crucial for understanding atomic structures, developing quantum computing, and advancing technologies like MRI.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Griffiths, D. J. (2017). <em>Introduction to Quantum Mechanics</em>. Cambridge University Press.<br>
        - Sakurai, J. J., & Napolitano, J. (2020). <em>Modern Quantum Mechanics</em>. Cambridge University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="102">102. Robotics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Robotics is the field of engineering and technology focused on the design, construction, and operation of robots.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Automation:</strong> Use of robots for performing repetitive tasks with precision and efficiency.<br>
        - <strong>Artificial Intelligence (AI):</strong> Integration of AI to enable robots to perform complex tasks and make decisions.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Robotics is used in manufacturing, medical surgery, space exploration, and consumer electronics.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Siciliano, B., & Khatib, O. (2016). <em>Springer Handbook of Robotics</em>. Springer.<br>
        - Russell, S., & Norvig, P. (2016). <em>Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach</em>. Pearson.
    </p>

    <h2 id="103">103. Space Exploration</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Space exploration involves the discovery and exploration of celestial structures through the use of astronomy and space technologies.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Milestones</strong><br>
        - <strong>Moon Landing:</strong> The Apollo 11 mission's success in landing the first humans on the Moon in 1969.<br>
        - <strong>Mars Rovers:</strong> Robotic missions like Curiosity and Perseverance exploring Mars.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Space exploration enhances our understanding of the universe, develops new technologies, and seeks to identify potentially habitable planets.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Chaikin, A. (1994). <em>A Man on the Moon: The Voyages of the Apollo Astronauts</em>. Penguin Books.<br>
        - Musk, E. (2020). <em>Elon Musk: Tesla, SpaceX, and the Quest for a Fantastic Future</em>. Ashlee Vance.
    </p>

    <h2 id="104">104. Statistics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Statistics is the science of collecting, analyzing, interpreting, and presenting data.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Descriptive Statistics:</strong> Methods for summarizing and describing data.<br>
        - <strong>Inferential Statistics:</strong> Techniques for making predictions or inferences about a population based on a sample.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Statistics is used in various fields, including research, business, and social sciences, to make informed decisions based on data analysis.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Moore, D. S., McCabe, G. P., & Craig, B. A. (2017). <em>Introduction to the Practice of Statistics</em>. W.H. Freeman and Company.<br>
        - Montgomery, D. C., & Runger, G. C. (2010). <em>Applied Statistics and Probability for Engineers</em>. Wiley.
    </p>

    <h2 id="105">105. Sustainability</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Sustainability focuses on meeting the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Principles</strong><br>
        - <strong>Environmental Protection:</strong> Practices that aim to conserve natural resources and reduce environmental impact.<br>
        - <strong>Social Equity:</strong> Ensuring fair treatment and opportunities for all people.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Sustainability is applied in various sectors, including energy, agriculture, and urban planning, to promote long-term ecological balance.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Sachs, J. D. (2015). <em>The Age of Sustainable Development</em>. Columbia University Press.<br>
        - Rockström, J., et al. (2009). <em>A Safe Operating Space for Humanity</em>. Nature.
    </p>

    <h2 id="106">106. Thermodynamics</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Thermodynamics is the branch of physics that deals with the relationships between heat, work, and energy.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Laws</strong><br>
        - <strong>First Law:</strong> Energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transferred or transformed.<br>
        - <strong>Second Law:</strong> The entropy of an isolated system always increases over time.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Thermodynamics is essential for designing engines, refrigerators, and understanding chemical reactions and phase transitions.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Callen, H. B. (1985). <em>Thermodynamics and an Introduction to Thermostatistics</em>. Wiley.<br>
        - Atkins, P., & Friedman, R. (2011). <em>Molecular Thermodynamics of Biochemical Reactions</em>. Oxford University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="107">107. Tourism</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Tourism involves the activities of people traveling to and staying in places outside their usual environment for leisure, business, or other purposes.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Aspects</strong><br>
        - <strong>Destination Management:</strong> Strategies for promoting and managing tourist destinations.<br>
        - <strong>Sustainable Tourism:</strong> Practices that aim to minimize the negative impacts of tourism on the environment and local cultures.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Tourism impacts local economies, cultures, and environments, and involves various sectors, including transportation, hospitality, and recreation.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Cooper, C., et al. (2008). <em>Tourism: Principles and Practice</em>. Pearson.<br>
        - Hall, C. M., & Page, S. J. (2014). <em>The Geography of Tourism and Recreation: Environment, Place, and Space</em>. Routledge.
    </p>

    <h2 id="108">108. Urban Studies</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Urban studies is the multidisciplinary field that examines cities and urban life.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Areas</strong><br>
        - <strong>Urban Planning:</strong> Design and regulation of land use and the built environment.<br>
        - <strong>Social Dynamics:</strong> Analysis of social interactions and demographics within urban settings.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Urban studies inform policies on housing, transportation, and infrastructure to improve the quality of life in urban areas.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Glaeser, E. L. (2011). <em>Triumph of the City: How Our Greatest Invention Makes Us Richer, Smarter, Greener, Healthier, and Happier</em>. Penguin Books.<br>
        - Harvey, D. (2012). <em>Rebel Cities: From the Right to the City to the Urban Revolution</em>. Verso.
    </p>

    <h2 id="109">109. Virtual Reality</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Virtual reality (VR) is an immersive technology that simulates a three-dimensional environment using computer technology.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Components</strong><br>
        - <strong>Head-Mounted Displays:</strong> Devices worn on the head that display VR content.<br>
        - <strong>Motion Tracking:</strong> Systems that track users' movements and adjust the VR environment accordingly.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>VR is used in gaming, education, healthcare, and training simulations to create interactive and immersive experiences.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Burdea, G., & Coiffet, P. (2003). <em>Virtual Reality Technology</em>. Wiley.<br>
        - Sherman, W. R., & Craig, A. B. (2018). <em>Understanding Virtual Reality: Interface, Application, and Design</em>. Morgan Kaufmann.
    </p>

    <h2 id="110">110. World History</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>World history studies the history of human civilization from a global perspective.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Themes</strong><br>
        - <strong>Civilizations and Empires:</strong> Examination of major civilizations and their impacts on world history.<br>
        - <strong>Global Interactions:</strong> Analysis of how different regions and cultures have influenced each other throughout history.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>World history provides insights into cultural, political, and economic developments that have shaped the modern world.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Jones, E. L. (2003). <em>The European Miracle: Environments, Economies, and Geopolitics in the History of Europe and Asia</em>. Cambridge University Press.<br>
        - Wright, J. (2004). <em>A Short History of Progress</em>. House of Anansi Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="111">111. Xenophobia</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>Xenophobia is the irrational fear or hatred of people from other countries or cultures.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Aspects</strong><br>
        - <strong>Social Impact:</strong> Xenophobia can lead to discrimination, exclusion, and violence against individuals perceived as outsiders.<br>
        - <strong>Historical Context:</strong> Examines how xenophobic attitudes have influenced historical events and policies.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>Understanding xenophobia is essential for fostering inclusivity, promoting multiculturalism, and addressing prejudice and discrimination.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Essed, P. (1991). <em>Understanding Everyday Racism: An Interdisciplinary Theory</em>. Sage Publications.<br>
        - Mudde, C., & Kaltwasser, C. R. (2017). <em>Populism: A Very Short Introduction</em>. Oxford University Press.
    </p>

    <h2 id="112">112. X-ray Technology</h2>
    <p><strong>Overview</strong><br>X-ray technology uses high-energy electromagnetic radiation to view the internal structure of objects and bodies.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Uses</strong><br>
        - <strong>Medical Imaging:</strong> Used for diagnosing fractures, infections, and other conditions.<br>
        - <strong>Security Screening:</strong> Employed in airports and other security-sensitive areas to inspect baggage.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Applications</strong><br>X-ray technology is crucial in medicine, security, and industrial applications for non-destructive testing.</p>
    <p><strong>Sources</strong><br>
        - Gelfand, A. E., & Smith, A. F. M. (1990). <em>Bayesian Statistics: Principles, Models, and Applications</em>. Oxford University Press.<br>
        - Huda, W., & Ogden, K. M. (2019). <em>The Physics of Medical Imaging</em>. CRC Press.
    </p>
